Ian Badcoe wrote:

&gt;Hi Colin,
&gt;
&gt;At 11:54 02/10/2005, you wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;[...]
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;One notable problem was deciding on connection lengths, relative neuron
&gt;&gt;positions for new genes etc. in relation to where all of the current
&gt;&gt;neurons are in the decoded network. If you get this wrong then the
&gt;&gt;system performs a very inefficient search of the search space, e.g.
&gt;&gt;always connecting to the &#39;outer&#39; neurons at the ends of the 1D space.
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;At the moment I am addressing that by limiting all fIDs to a range of 0 - 1.
&gt;
&gt;Also, for the boards, I start the system with the 4 build-in boards (mine, 
&gt;yours, empty, our-of-range) positioned evenly through the range (.125, 
&gt;.375, .625, .875) so I know there are no outrageously large gaps...
&gt;  
&gt;
I think the problem grows with the size of the genome. As you branch off 
(branch in 1D space?) into new areas of space it becomes more difficult 
to think of a scheme that would result in attempts to connect into those 
potentially far away areas that isn&#39;t also really bad at exploring local 
space. There&#39;s probably a really simple elegant solution. Oh and I was 
never quite sure how many dimensions would work best, or in fact why I 
should use one continous space of N-dimensions at all.

&gt;&gt;I can&#39;t say whether this works due to other problems with my set up, but
&gt;&gt;it&#39;s definitely something I would like to get back to someday if I get time.
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;         It&#39;s good to know that great minds continue to think alike :)
&gt;  
&gt;
This is probably an indication that there is some underlying fundamental 
unified system that we are converging upon.... just kidding! Actually 
I&#39;m glad you put a smiley on the end of that sentence.

